Practical II: Extracting, Visualizing, and Analyzing Multiple Networks

Practical II: Extracting, Visualizing, and Analyzing Multiple Networks

Carel F.W. Peeters

Mathematical & Statistical Methods group Biometris
Wageningen University & Research
IBC2022 Short Course on Network Modeling for High-Dimensional Data

carel.peeters@wur.nl

July 10th, 2022

Preliminaries

This document contains a tutorial for Part II of the course on Network Modeling for High-Dimensional Data as given during the 31st International Biometric Conference.

Often, data consists of observations that are subject to class membership. Class membership may have different connotations. It may refer to certain sub-classes within a single data set such as disease subtypes. It may also designate different data sets or studies. Likewise, the class indicator may also refer to a conjunction of both subclass and study membership to form a two-way design of factors of interest (e.g., breast cancer subtypes present in a batch of study-specific data sets) (Bilgrau & Peeters et al., 2020). In such settings one may desire the joint estimation of multiple regularized precision matrices from (aggregated) high-dimensional data consisting of distinct classes. The learning goals for Part II are:

  1. To familiarize yourself with basic concepts in joint network modeling;
  2. To practice with joint modeling of multiple networks from high-dimensional data.

The slides, exercises, and this document form an integrated whole. The slides alternate between the presentation of methodology and corresponding exercises. This document, then, contains possible solutions to the exercises as well as additional explanations.

Packages

We again set the working directory to convenience and activate the required package:

## Set working directory to convenience
setwd(" ")

## Packages (install and invoke)
pkgs <- rownames(installed.packages())
if(!"rags2ridges" %in% pkgs) install.packages("rags2ridges")

The code recognizes if certain packages are missing from your package library and, if so, will install them automatically. Now, we need to load the package:

library(rags2ridges)

Throughout, we will again be using amenities provided by the rags2ridges package. This package provides a one-stop-shop for the extraction, visualization, and analysis of networks from high-dimensional data (Peeters et al.2022). The fused module in rags2ridges contains functions for joint network modeling. Its functions, suffixed with .fused, in many cases mirror the functions used in Part I. This Part then revolves around the extraction, visualization, and analysis of multiple networks. The exercises and code in this document are cumulative: each exercise and code block builds upon the preceding exercises and code. Code is contained in blocks and in-text references to functions, function arguments, and objects will be denoted as foo.

Exercise 1: Construct data and target lists

Throughout, we will be using metabolomics data on patients with Alzheimers Disease (AD) again. The data (de Leeuw & Peeters et al., 2017) are internally packaged in the ADdata object:

## Invoke data
data("ADdata", package = "rags2ridges")

We have data for 2 classes of AD patients (Class 1 and Class 2) and we have an interest in jointly estimating the class-specific precision matrices as a basis for joint (or integrative) network modeling. The data for AD class 1 patients consists of n1=40 observations on p=230 metabolic features. As we have seen in Part I, the data for AD class 2 patients consists of n2=87 observations on the same p=230 metabolic features. Many functions in the fused module take list-arguments. Specifically, we are in need of lists of class-specific target matrices and class-specific data matrices.

First, we retain the data for both AD classes. We scale the class-specific data, as the features have different scales and as the variability of the features may differ substantially. Again, as we have little a priori knowledge, we will keep the class-specific targets simple: Both classes are assigned an identity matrix as the target matrix.

## Subset
ADclass1 <- ADmetabolites[, sampleInfo$ApoEClass == "Class 1"]
ADclass2 <- ADmetabolites[, sampleInfo$ApoEClass == "Class 2"]

## Transpose and scale data
ADclass1 <- scale(t(ADclass1))
ADclass2 <- scale(t(ADclass2))

## Correlations for subsets
rAD1 <- cor(ADclass1)
rAD2 <- cor(ADclass2)

## Constructing list of correlation matrices
Rlist <- list(rAD1 = rAD1, rAD2 = rAD2)
samps <- c(nrow(ADclass1), nrow(ADclass2))

## Constructing list of target matrices and data
Tlist <- default.target.fused(Slist = Rlist, ns = samps, type = "DUPV")
Ylist <- list(AD1data = ADclass1, AD2data = ADclass2)

The constructed lists will be directly used in the estimation of class-specific precision matrices.

Extraction

Joint Network evaluation also basically has 3 steps: (i) extract, (ii) visualize, (iii) analyze. Extraction is about inferring the networks from the data. Visualization pertains to the effective graphical communication of the networks. Analysis pertains to descriptions and inference on properties of the retained networks. We will start with the fused extraction of joint networks.

Exercise 2: Find optimal fused precision matrices

As both classes consists of patients with AD, one would expect the network topologies of the respective groups to share some of their structure, while potentially differing in a number of (topological) locations of interest. The implemented joint estimation method (Bilgrau & Peeters et al., 2020) takes this explicitly into account. It extends ridge estimation of single precision matrices to the joint estimation of multiple precision matrices. It has a generalized penalty structure such that not only individual matrix regularization is controlled (through ridge penalties), but also the retainment of entry-wise similarities between classes (through fused penalties).

The optPenalty.fused function finds the optimal ridge and fusion penalty parameters via K-fold cross validation of the negative log-likelihood score. It does so by using multi-dimensional optimization routines. The penalty-values at which the K-fold cross-validated negative fused log-likelihood score is minimized are deemed optimal. If we, during the course, experience a lack of time, then we can load the FusedOptimal.Rdata object (included in the course materials). It contains optimal penalty values and class-specific precision matrices as obtained through a previous run of optPenalty.fused.

## If not enough time during session, we load the OPTf result from 'FusedOptimal.Rdata'
load("FusedOptimal.Rdata")

If we have enough time, we can use the following code, which contains the call to optPenalty.fused that gives the results contained in the FusedOptimal.Rdata object. This specific call uses 10-fold cross-validation and a penalty matrix that specifies class-specific ridge penalties and a single fusion penalty for the classes.

## Finding optimal penalty parameters and precision matrices
## Will take a few minutes (depending on your machine)
set.seed(8910)
OPTf <- optPenalty.fused(
  Ylist     = Ylist, 
  Tlist     = Tlist, 
  lambda    = as.matrix(cbind(c("ridge1", "fusion"),c("fusion", "ridge2"))),
  cv.method = "kCV",
  k         = 10,
  verbose   = FALSE)

Either way, we now have the OPTf object to our disposal. OPTf$Plist is itself a list containing the class-specific precision matrices under the optimal penalties. OPTf$lambda.unique contains the optimal penalty-values.

## Optimal penalty values
OPTf$lambda.unique
      ridge1       fusion       ridge2 
1.973739e+01 2.085230e-19 1.693029e+01
  1. What do the penalty-values tell us?


  1. The ridge penalties are large relative to the fusion penalty. Hence, the penalty values emphasize individual regularization over retainment of entry-wise similarities, indicating quite strong differences in class-specific precision matrices.


Of course, we could look at the conditioning of each of the precision matrices with the CNplot function (they are well-conditioned). Again, heatmaps of the optimal class-specific precision matrices are easily obtained through usage of the edgeHeat function.

## Heatmaps of optimal precision matrices
edgeHeat(OPTf$Plist$AD1data, diag = FALSE, textsize = 3)

edgeHeat(OPTf$Plist$AD2data, diag = FALSE, textsize = 3)

  1. What do you notice from the heatmaps regarding the structure of the class-specific precision matrices?


  1. The heatmaps seem to indicate that the AD Class 1 precision matrix is more erratic (less structured).

Exercise 3: Extract class-specific networks

After obtaining class-specific precision matrices, we again need to determine their support in order to extract class-specific networks. Support determination in the fused setting is performed by the sparsify.fused function. Its arguments are analogous to the arguments for the sparsify function. We again use local FDR thresholding and set FDRcut quite high: .999. The sparsify.fused function returns, for all classes considered, both the sparsified precision matrix and the sparsified partial correlation matrix.

## Threshold the optimal precision matrices
## Retain those elements whose posterior probability of being present >= .999
P0s <- sparsify.fused(OPTf$Plist, 
                      threshold = "localFDR", 
                      FDRcut    = .999,
                      verbose   = FALSE)
- Retained elements:  94 
- Corresponding to 0.36 % of possible edges 
 
- Retained elements:  289 
- Corresponding to 1.1 % of possible edges
  1. How many edges do we retain in each of the class networks?


  1. We retain, under our local FDR threshold, 94 edges in the network for class 1 and 289 edges in the network for class 2.


The heatmaps of, say, the class-specific sparsified partial correlation matrices are easily obtained:

## Heatmaps of sparsified partial correlation matrices
edgeHeat(P0s$AD1data$sparseParCor, diag = FALSE, textsize = 3)

edgeHeat(P0s$AD2data$sparseParCor, diag = FALSE, textsize = 3)

Visualization

After estimation we are again interested in visualization. When visualizing multiple networks over the same features, there are some additional issues to think of (in addition to layout, coloring, etc.). One such issue is the possible retainment of coordinates over class-specific graphs.

Exercise 4: Visualize the retained networks in the same node-coordinates

The main function for visualization, Ugraph, also supports visual comparison of class-specific networks. Ugraph also outputs the layout-coordinates of the network that is visualized. This enables the visualization of class-specific networks in the same coordinates. At times, this may be insightful as it allows one to visually track differential connections between class-specific networks. In order to do so for the AD Class 1 and AD class 2 networks, we first use the Union function. This convenience function subsets 2 square matrices (over the same features) to the union of features that have nonzero row (column) entries (i.e., to features implied in graphical connections). This allows one to prune both networks to those features that are connected in at least 1 of them. The AD Class 2 network will determine the coordinates for the AD Class 1 network, as the heatmaps seem to indicate that the former is the most structured one. Again, we use node-colorings to heighten the information-density of the visualization. We then get the network for the Class 2 data:

## Visualizing classes with same coordinates helps (visual) comparison
## First, need to retain union of features over class-networks
TST <- Union(P0s$AD1data$sparseParCor, P0s$AD2data$sparseParCor)

## Convenience, rename sparsified partial correlation matrices over union
PCclass1 <- TST$M1subset
PCclass2 <- TST$M2subset

## Set coloring
Colors <- rownames(PCclass2)
Colors[grep("Amine", rownames(PCclass2))]     <- "lightblue"
Colors[grep("Org.Acid", rownames(PCclass2))]  <- "orange"
Colors[grep("Lip", rownames(PCclass2))]       <- "yellow"
Colors[grep("Ox.Stress", rownames(PCclass2))] <- "purple"

## Visualize first network, retain coordinates
set.seed(111213)
Coords <- Ugraph(PCclass2, 
                 type   = "fancy", 
                 lay    = "layout_with_fr", 
                 Vcolor = Colors, 
                 prune  = FALSE, 
                 Vsize  = 7, 
                 Vcex   = .3,
                 main   = "AD Class 2")

  1. The network for the Class 2 data strongly resembles the network for the Class 2 data obtained in Part I. However, now we have a slightly lesser number of connections (289 against 310 before). Can you reason why?


  1. This is due to the fused estimation: There is some retainment of entry-wise similarities between the Class 1 and Class 2 networks.


The coordinates of the network for the Class 2 data are contained in the Coords object. By specifying lay = NULL and setting coords = Coords in the Ugraph call on the sparsified partial correlation matrix for Class 1, we obtain a visualization of the network for the Class 1 data in the same coordinates as the network for the Class 2 data.

## Visualize second network with retained coordinates
catchcoords <-
Ugraph(PCclass1, 
       type   = "fancy",
       lay    = NULL,
       coords = Coords,
       Vcolor = Colors, 
       prune  = FALSE, 
       Vsize  = 7, 
       Vcex   = .3,
       main   = "AD Class 1")

Exercise 5: Visualize the differential graph

In Many instances, one may be interested in network-connections that are specific to a certain class. It would then be insightful to make a differential network. In such a network the edges are color-coded according to class-specific presence. The DiffGraph function visualizes in a single graph the edges that are unique to the respective classes. The unique edges are color-coded according to class-membership. Dashed lines indicate negative precision/partial correlation elements while solid lines indicate positive precision/partial correlation elements. The arguments mirror the arguments of Ugraph. The coordinates of the network for the Class 2 are again used for layout purposes (by specifying lay = NULL and setting coords = Coords).

## Visualize the edges unique to each class
DiffGraph(PCclass1, PCclass2,
          lay    = NULL,
          coords = Coords,
          Vcolor = Colors, 
          Vsize  = 7, 
          Vcex   = .3,
          main   = "Differential Network")

  1. The call to DiffGraph above used default edge colors. Can you tell which edge colorings belong to which AD class?


  1. The edges unique to AD Class 2 are depicted in green. The edges unique to AD Class 1 are depicted in red.


For comparison we could visualize the networks for Class 1, Class 2, and the differential graph side-by-side all in the same coordinates:

## Plot the class networks and their difference network in same window
set.seed(111213)
opar <- par(mfrow = c(1, 3))
Coords <- Ugraph(PCclass2, 
                 type   = "fancy", 
                 lay    = "layout_with_fr", 
                 Vcolor = Colors, 
                 prune  = FALSE, 
                 Vsize  = 7, 
                 Vcex   = .3,
                 main   = "AD Class 2")
catchcoords <-
  Ugraph(PCclass1, 
         type   = "fancy",
         lay    = NULL,
         coords = Coords,
         Vcolor = Colors, 
         prune  = FALSE, 
         Vsize  = 7, 
         Vcex   = .3,
         main   = "AD Class 1")
DiffGraph(PCclass1, PCclass2,
          lay    = NULL,
          coords = Coords,
          Vcolor = Colors, 
          Vsize  = 7, 
          Vcex   = .3,
          main   = "Differential Network")

par(opar)

Analysis

The analyses at the node, path and community level performed in Part 1 have natural extensions to the situation in which we have multiple class-specific networks. We will give examples for the node and community level. Subsequently, a simple global (or network-level) analysis is performed.

Exercise 6: Compare the top node-degrees for the class-specific networks

The GGMnetworkStats.fused function calculates various network statistics from a list of sparse precision/partial correlation matrices. It returns a data.frame with the slotnames of the input list prefixed to the column-names.

## Make list of sparse Partial correlation (or precision) matrices
PC0list <- list(PCclass1 = PCclass1, PCclass2 = PCclass2)

## GGMnetworks.fused
## The warning can be ignored: standard warning when calculating closeness 
##     centrality for a disconnected graph
NwkSTATSList <- GGMnetworkStats.fused(PC0list)
Warning in closeness(CIG): At centrality.c:2784 :closeness centrality is not
well-defined for disconnected graphs

Warning in closeness(CIG): At centrality.c:2784 :closeness centrality is not
well-defined for disconnected graphs
## Compare top degree centralities
DegreesAD1  <- data.frame(rownames(NwkSTATSList), 
                          NwkSTATSList$PCclass1.degree)
DegreesAD2  <- data.frame(rownames(NwkSTATSList), 
                          NwkSTATSList$PCclass2.degree)
DegreesAD1o <- DegreesAD1[order(DegreesAD1[, 2], decreasing = TRUE), ]
DegreesAD2o <- DegreesAD2[order(DegreesAD2[, 2], decreasing = TRUE), ]
head(DegreesAD1o, 7)

  1. At first glance the degree distributions seem to differ. We will assess this with a simple test in Exercise 8.


Exercise 7: Find and visualize communities for the class-specific networks

We can apply the Communities function to each class-specific sparsified matrix in order to find (and visualize) the communities for each class-specific network:

## Finding feature-communities on the basis of betweenness-centrality
set.seed(141516)
opar <- par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
CommyC1 <- Communities(PCclass1, Vcolor = Colors, Vsize = 7,  Vcex = .3,
                       main = "Modules AD Class 1")
CommyC2 <- Communities(PCclass2, Vcolor = Colors, Vsize = 7,  Vcex = .3,
                       main = "Modules AD Class 2")

par(opar)

## Peeking at memberships can be done through:
#- CommyC1$membership
#- CommyC2$membership
  1. What conclusion is emerging in this latest visualization?


  1. The emerging picture is that the network for AD Class 2 is structured and modular while the network for AD Class 1 appears unstructured and loosely arranged.

Exercise 8: Compare the degree distributions for the class-specific networks

Juxtaposing 2 networks also allows for tests on global network properties. Simple testing could be done to assess, for example, differences in degree distributions or inherent randomness of the networks. Here, we explore simple testing regarding degree distributions. We can plot the degree distributions of the respective networks to see that these seem different. For the Class 2 network, most nodes have a similar degree. For the Class 1 network, the degree distribution seems to follow more of a power-law than a binomial distribution.

## Testing closely corresponds to assessing global network properties
## Plot degree distributions
plot(density(DegreesAD1[, 2]), col = "red",  xlim = c(-1, 8),
     xlab = "Degree", main = "")
lines(density(DegreesAD2[, 2]), col = "blue")
legenda <- c("AD class 1", "AD class 2")
legend(5, .5, legend = legenda, lwd = rep(1, 2), lty = rep(1, 2), 
       col = c("red", "blue"), cex = .9)

We can perform a simple Wilcoxon test to see if the distribution of the difference in degrees is symmetric about 0. We specify a one-sided alternative as we believe that the degree location of Class 2 is shifted to the right of the location for Class 1.

## Testing degree distributions with dependent 2-group Wilcoxon Signed Rank Test
wilcox.test(DegreesAD1[, 2], DegreesAD2[, 2], paired = TRUE,
            alternative = "less")

    Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction

data:  DegreesAD1[, 2] and DegreesAD2[, 2]
V = 444, p-value < 2.2e-16
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0
  1. What do you conclude on the basis of the test?


  1. We reject the null hypothesis. The true location shift seems to be less than zero. Hence, we conclude that the degree location of Class 1 is shifted to the left of the location for Class 2. Or, conversely, the degree location of Class 2 is shifted to the right of the location for Class 1.


Hence, the degree distributions imply that the network for Class 1 is more loosely connected. The lack of signal, or diffusion of signal, gives that the Class 1 network seems more random or erratic. Class 2 has a known genetic predisposition for AD which may translate in relatively stable aberrations/amplifications across the metabolome. Class 1 has no known genetic predisposition for AD. The group is thus likely heterogeneous in disease aetiology, which may be a possible explanation for the lack of cohesiveness at the metabolic level.

Recap and look ahead

In Part I we have focused on the extraction, visualization, and analysis of a single network. In Part II we have focused on the joint extraction, visualization, and analysis of multiple networks. Network evaluation can be very insightful. However, be aware that the graphical methods should be largely viewed as exploratory, theory or hypothesis-generating techniques. Any tentative findings they produce are ideally subjected to further research and experimentation. Part III will follow up with the network cycle for time-course data.
